unixpgmr 2020-02-15 13:10
@SupremePancakes When I was in school, I had to take a database class. You optimize (reduce redundancy of data) designs in what is called "normal forms". There are 5 levels of normal forms. We had to do a project. I did mine in 3rd ( and a few tables in 4th) normal form. My professor knocked points off for not doing it in 5th normal form. I argued that while 5th is nice, it isn't practical for business because of all the joins you had to do. He said not true. Well, in my experience, I was right. I have yet to see a database being used in a business in 5th normal form. The moral of the story is, yes academia teaches you a lot of neat stuff, but some of it is impractical in real world settings. Keep that in mind.
Wow, that kind of ended up a wall of text. Sorry about that.

unixpgmr 2020-07-02 14:55
Man, I just figure out a bug I was having with an API call. The called looked like this:
curl -s -X GET --url ${apiUrl} -H accept: application/json -H "x-apikeys: ${apiAuth}"
Curl kept giving me a return code of 6 which is " url: (6) Could not resolve host: application error after this command" However, was still getting proper data back from the API call. My google fu finally kicked in and I discovered that I should NOT have a space between "accept:" and "application/json". The proper URL call should be:
curl -s -X GET --url ${apiUrl} -H accept:application/json -H "x-apikeys: ${apiAuth}"
bees 2020-07-02 16:55
oh my god
that is awful
is that against rfc2616?
unixpgmr 2020-07-02 19:01
I don't think so. A strict reading of rfc2616:
HTTP uses Internet Media Types [17] in the Content-Type (section 14.17) and Accept (section 14.1) header fields in order to provide open and extensible data typing and type negotiation. media-type = type "/" subtype *( ";" parameter ) type = token subtype = token Parameters MAY follow the type/subtype in the form of attribute/value pairs (as defined in section 3.6). The type, subtype, and parameter attribute names are case- insensitive. Parameter values might or might not be case-sensitive, depending on the semantics of the parameter name. Linear white space (LWS) MUST NOT be used between the type and subtype, nor between an attribute and its value.
Leads me to believe that no white space is allowed. However, I have gotten this to work for other APIs. So I suspect it depends heavily upon the server receiving the request.
bees 2020-07-02 19:10
interesting!
yeah the RFC is maddening because there are literally headers that contradict that parse definition: e.g.
The Content-Type entity-header field indicates the media type of the entity-body sent to the recipient or, in the case of the HEAD method, the media type that would have been sent had the request been a GET. Content-Type = "Content-Type" ":" media-type Media types are defined in section 3.7. An example of the field is Content-Type: text/html; charset=ISO-8859-4
really should be more rigorous with the definition, maybe, you know, express it in BNF

Regardless of your workflow, it is very helpful to measure two nonstandard things: 1. The ratio between feature work and technical debt per work unit 2. How easy it is to shift a task from one member to another in a team
1

further, if teams are dialed in, and helping each other, every task should be fungible, able to be passed to each other. If not, one should spend more time on cross training and acceptance criteria authorship
